BLUETONGUE - MACEDONIA: OIE REPORT
**********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 10 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/alerte/en_mkd081001.HTM>

Disease never previously reported
---------------------------------
Information received on 5 Oct 2001 from Dr Zoran Danevski, Director of
Veterinary Service, Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Water Economy,
Skopje:
Report date: 5 Oct 2001.
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 26 Sep 2001.
Location and No. of outbreaks:
3 in Ogud village, region of Kriva Palanka,
1 in Krstov Dol village, region of Kriva Palanka.
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
No. of susceptible: 300
No. of cases: 16
No. of deaths: 2
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Veterinary Institute of Skopje.
B. Diagnostic tests used: competitive ELISA with monoclonal antibodies.
Control measures:
As of the day of the establishment of the suspicion on the presence of the
disease, Macedonian veterinary authorities have implemented precautionary
measures to prevent the spread of the disease. A total stand still of the
susceptible animals was ordered in the flocks where positive diagnosis was
established.
After the laboratory confirmation, the following measures were implemented:
- killing and destruction of the animals that showed clinical signs as well
as animals suspected of being infected;
- establishment of 20 km protection zone;
- movement ban of susceptible animals within protection zone;
- desinsectisation within protection zone;
- clinical investigation on the presence of the disease in the whole country;
- surveillance for the presence of the vector of the disease in the whole
country;
- serological surveillance for the disease.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[It would be helpful to know which species were involved in this outbreak.
Use of the word "flocks" would imply sheep and/or goats, but a definitive
declaration of whether cattle, sheep, and/or goats are involved would
complete the report. - Mod.PC]
